## Quality Issues

The dataset contains several quality issues that are commonly found in real-world data collected from surveys.

One issue is inconsistent text entries. Although predefined categories were available for employment type, some respondents entered their own descriptions such as *"muusow ma shaqeeyo,"* *"Hooshada ma ahan engineering ee Ai g See camal wye,"* and *"no one works but."* These responses should be standardized into consistent categories before analysis.

The dataset also contains **formatting inconsistencies**. For example, one respondent entered the number of people under eighteen as **"01"** instead of **"1."** Likewise, one respondent entered screen time as **"078"** rather than **"78."** Although these values are numerically similar, they should be standardized during preprocessing.

There are several possible outliers in the numerical variables. One household reported 60 household members, while another reported 20 children under the age of 18. Similarly, screen-time values of 66, 78, and 35 hours appear unusually high for a typical weekday and may require verification. These records should be examined carefully to determine whether they represent genuine responses or data entry errors.

The dataset also contains mixed categorical values because some respondents answered in English while others answered in Somali. Standardizing language and category names would improve consistency.

Although no obvious duplicate records were observed from the sample provided, duplicate responses should still be checked before analysis. Missing values should also be inspected once the complete dataset has been collected because incomplete survey responses are common in questionnaire-based research.

Overall, the dataset reflects authentic survey responses and therefore provides an excellent example for learning data cleaning, preprocessing, and exploratory data analysis.

